"{\"uid\": \"canberratimes.com.au-story-8759750-oarful-olympic-medals-stolen-from-rowing-legend-drew-ginn\", \"text\": \"Your digital subscription includes access to content from all our websites in your region.\\r Access unlimited news content and The Canberra Times app. Premium subscribers also enjoy interactive puzzles and access to the digital version of our print edition - Today's Paper.  Police have arrested and charged a man following the alleged theft of four Olympic gold medals fromAustralian champion rower Drew Ginn.  Loginor signup to continue reading  Mr Ginn was a member of the Oarsome Foursome, a highly successful rowing crew, earning a gold medal at the 1996 Atlanta, 2004 Athens and 2008 Beijing Olympics as well as a silver medal at the 2012 London games.  The medals, allegedly stolen from a black Land Rover parked in the inner-city Melbourne suburb of Docklands, were in Mr Ginn's car after a speaking engagement at a school, he told police.  \\\"These are unbelievably rare items with significant sentimental value,\\\" detective sergeant Timothy Reiher said.  \\\"Olympic medals are awarded to the best of the best and are priceless to their recipients,\\\" he said.  Investigators believe the thieves broke into the 49-year-old's car between 9pm on September 6 and 5am on September 7 while it was parked on Cumberland Street.  A Rip Curl wetsuit, a Go Pro camera and Sony headphones were also allegedly stolen.  \\\"We ask that people look out for these medals in pawn shops and online selling platforms,\\\" detective sergeant Reiher said.  On September 11, police said a 47-year-old Windsor man, who was wanted on warrant over the alleged offending, was arrested by police in Brunswick.  He has been charged with theft from motor vehicle, obtain property by deception, obtain financial advantage by deception and handle stolen goods, police said.  He will face Melbourne Magistrates' Court on November 29.  Neither the Olympic medals or any of the other allegedly stolen property has been recovered.  Anyone with information that could assist in locating the stolen medals is urged to contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000 or make a report atwww.crimestoppersvic.com.au  Anna Houlahan reports on crime and social issues affecting regional and remote Australia in her role as national crime reporter at Australian Community Media (ACM). She was ACM's Trainee of the Year in 2023 and, aside from reporting on crime, has travelled the country as a journalist for Explore Travel Magazine. Reach out with news or updates to anna.houlahan@austcommunitymedia.com.au  Anna Houlahan reports on crime and social issues affecting regional and remote Australia in her role as national crime reporter at Australian Community Media (ACM). She was ACM's Trainee of the Year in 2023 and, aside from reporting on crime, has travelled the country as a journalist for Explore Travel Magazine. Reach out with news or updates to anna.houlahan@austcommunitymedia.com.au  Daily  Today's top stories curated by our news team. Also includes evening update.  As it happens  Do not miss updates on news about the Public Service.  Weekdays  Grab a quick bite of today's latest news from around the region and the nation.  Weekdays  Catch up on the news of the day and unwind with great reading for your evening.  Weekly  Get the editor's insights: what's happening & why it matters.  Twice weekly  Stay in the know on news that matters to you with twice weekly newsletters from The Senior.  Weekly  Going out or staying in? Find out what's on.  Daily  The latest news, results & expert analysis.  Daily  Your exclusive preview of David Pope's latest cartoon.  Weekly  Join our weekly poll for Canberra Times readers.  Weekly  We have selected the best reading for your weekend.  Weekly  Get the latest property and development news here.  Weekly  Every Saturday and Tuesday, explore destinations deals, tips & travel writing to transport you around the globe.  Weekdays  Sharp. Close to the gro